 Custom Init and Destroy Methods:

You can specify custom initialization and destruction methods in your bean definition (especially with Java-based config).
Example:

@Bean(initMethod = "customInit", destroyMethod = "customDestroy")
public EmailService emailService() {
    return new EmailService();
}

public class EmailService {
    public void customInit() { /* custom initialization */ }
    public void customDestroy() { /* custom cleanup */ }
}


b. BeanPostProcessor:
Purpose: Allows you to add custom logic before and after Spring initializes any bean.
How it works: Implement the BeanPostProcessor interface and override its methods.
Example:

@Component
public class CustomBeanPostProcessor implements BeanPostProcessor {
    @Override
    public Object postProcessBeforeInitialization(Object bean, String beanName) {
        // logic before initialization
        return bean;
    }

    @Override
    public Object postProcessAfterInitialization(Object bean, String beanName) {
        // logic after initialization
        return bean;
    }
}

Use case: Logging, proxying, or modifying beans during their lifecycle.